{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54a2844d-ddf8-45b8-8b07-3f158124e7de","content":"With **MSTest 3.8.2**, the recommended pattern:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via a constructor parameter (MSTest v3+ auto-injects it).\n- **Sync init** — use `[TestInitialize]` (or the constructor for non-test-framework setup).\n- **Async init** — `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task`.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; } // auto-injected by MSTest v3\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (e.g., seed a database, start a service)\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest() => Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task AsyncTest() => await Task.CompletedTask;\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor runs first (sync), then `[TestInitialize]` runs (supports `async Task`).\n- For class-level one-time setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (also supports `async Task`).\n- For cleanup, `[TestCleanup]` and `[ClassCleanup]` mirror the pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d360e9b5-0df4-4e3e-9ac5-f1006164c92b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `TestContext` property. In MSTest v3+, you can inject `TestContext` via constructor.\n\n2. **Sync initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Async initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task` return type in MSTest v3.\n\nLet me give them a clear, concise answer.","outputTokens":473},"id":"cb6d284a-740a-48b1-afe6-8fd0ab789dd7","timestamp":"2026-04-05T02:01:45.121Z","parentId":"61199cd3-c91e-41d1-aae2-5e2c0d20a1f2"}
